  <discussion>Plants in open, alpine and arctic habitats often have leaf blades orbiculate to
        orbiculate-ovate, 10–20 mm, apices obtuse, anthers ca. 1 mm, and styles 3–4.5 mm, and have
        been called Orthilia secunda subsp. obtusata. E. Haber (1972) concluded that these
        characters vary too freely among populations to warrant distinction.</discussion>
  <discussion>The Southern Carrier of British Columbia made a decoction from the roots, which they
        used as an eyewash (D. E. Moerman 1998).</discussion>
